Angiotensin-converting enzyme.label: Angiotensin-converting enzyme
Angiotensin-converting enzyme.description: Angiotensin-converting enzyme increases blood pressure by causing blood vessels to constrict. It does that by converting angiotensin I to angiotensin II, which constricts the vessels. Wikipedia

Ornithine decarboxylase.label: Ornithine decarboxylase
Ornithine decarboxylase.description: The enzyme ornithine decarboxylase catalyzes the decarboxylation of ornithine to form putrescine. This reaction is the committed step in polyamine synthesis. In humans, this protein has 461 amino acids and forms a homodimer. Wikipedia

Pyruvate carboxylase.label: Pyruvate carboxylase
Pyruvate carboxylase.description:
Pyruvate carboxylase is an enzyme of the ligase class that catalyzes the irreversible carboxylation of pyruvate to form oxaloacetate.
Pyruvic acid
Oxaloacetic acid
It is an important anaplerotic reaction that creates oxaloacetate from pyruvate. Wikipedia

DNA ligase.label: DNA ligase
DNA ligase.description: In molecular biology, DNA ligase is a specific type of enzyme, a ligase, that facilitates the joining of DNA strands together by catalyzing the formation of a phosphodiester bond. Wikipedia

Hexokinase.label: Hexokinase
Hexokinase.description: A hexokinase is an enzyme that phosphorylates hexoses, forming hexose phosphate. In most organisms, glucose is the most important substrate of hexokinases, and glucose-6-phosphate the most important product. Wikipedia

5-alpha reductase.label: 5-alpha reductase
5-alpha reductase.description: 5α-reductases, also known as 3-oxo-5α-steroid 4-dehydrogenases, are enzymes involved in steroid metabolism. They participate in 3 metabolic pathways bile acid biosynthesis, androgen and estrogen metabolism, and prostate cancer. Wikipedia

Diguanylate cyclase.label: Diguanylate cyclase
Diguanylate cyclase.description:
In enzymology, diguanylate cyclase, also known as diguanylate kinase, is an enzyme that catalyzes the chemical reaction

Alkaline phosphatase.label: Alkaline phosphatase
Alkaline phosphatase.description: Alkaline phosphatase is a hydrolase enzyme responsible for removing phosphate groups from many types of molecules, including nucleotides, proteins, and alkaloids. The process of removing the phosphate group is called dephosphorylation. Wikipedia

Nucleoside-diphosphate kinase.label: Nucleoside-diphosphate kinase
Nucleoside-diphosphate kinase.description: Nucleoside-diphosphate kinases are enzymes that catalyze the exchange of phosphate groups between different nucleoside diphosphates. Wikipedia

G protein-coupled receptor kinase.label: G protein-coupled receptor kinase
G protein-coupled receptor kinase.description: G protein-coupled receptor kinases are a family of protein kinases that regulate the activity of G protein-coupled receptors by phosphorylating their intracellular domains after their associated G proteins have been released and activated. Wikipedia

reductase.label: Reductase
reductase.description: A reductase is an enzyme that catalyzes a reduction reaction. Wikipedia

Aconitase.label: Aconitase
Aconitase.description:
Aconitase is an enzyme that catalyses the stereo-specific isomerization of citrate to isocitrate via cis-aconitate in the tricarboxylic acid cycle, a non-redox-active process.
Citric acid
Aconitic acid

Fructose-bisphosphate aldolase.label: Fructose-bisphosphate aldolase
Fructose-bisphosphate aldolase.description: Fructose-bisphosphate aldolase, often just aldolase, is an enzyme catalyzing a reversible reaction that splits the aldol, fructose 1,6-bisphosphate, into the triose phosphates dihydroxyacetone phosphate and glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate. Wikipedia

Chlorophyllase.label: Chlorophyllase
Chlorophyllase.description: Chlorophyllase is the key enzyme in chlorophyll metabolism. It is a membrane protein that is commonly known as Chlase and systematically known as chlorophyll chlorophyllidohydrolase. Wikipedia
